    "body": "> Mind that `char` is not, necessarily, signed, this depends on the architecture's C ABI. And no matter, what, it is always seen as a separate type from both `signed char` and `unsigned char`. This difference between platforms tends to give a lot of subtle issues (including a security in the SOCKS5 code, historically) so I think it's best to use `uint8_t` as a byte type where remotely possible.\r\n\r\nJust adding a reference: interested readers might want to check out this [write-up on the SOCKS5 issue CVE-2017-18350](https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2019-November/017453.html) @laanwj mentions above.\r\n\r\nFWIW, I agree 100% with what was said above. Or more explicitly: explicit (`uint8_t`) is better! :)",
